+{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01WSEMrh1rhBK9kK5r5jo6wV","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I'll implement `solveCounter`. The approach:\n- Gaussian elimination over GF(p) where p is prime\n- Modular inverse via Fermat's little theorem: a^(-1) = a^(p-2) mod p\n- After RREF, enumerate free variables (each from 0 to p-1) to find minimum total presses\n- With up to 40 free variables and p up to 97, brute force enumeration of p^numFree is infeasible for any numFree > ~3\n- Need meet-in-the-middle or similar approach\n\nFor GF(p), the enumeration space for free variables is p^numFree. With p=97 and numFree=2, that's 9409 — fine. With numFree=5, that's 97^5 = ~8.6 billion — too slow.\n\nFor the optimization problem: we want to minimize sum(result[i]) where result is a solution vector over GF(p).\n\nAfter RREF, pivot variables are determined by free variables. For each pivot row r:\n  pivotVal[r] = target[r] - sum(coeff[r][fi] * freeVal[fi]) mod p\n\nThe total presses = sum(pivotVals) + sum(freeVals).\n\nThe \"presses\" for each button is its value in [0, p-1]. We want minimum sum over all values.\n\nThis is a harder optimization problem than GF(2) because each variable can take p values.\n\nFor the meet-in-the-middle approach: split free vars into two halves. For each half, enumerate all p^halfSize assignments. For each, compute a \"signature\" (the effect on pivot rows, which is a vector in GF(p)^rank). Then combine.\n\nWith halfSize = 20 and p = 97, p^20 is astronomically large. Not feasible.\n\nSo I need a different approach. Let me think...\n\nWith 40 buttons and 40 lights, rank ≤ 40, numFree = m - rank. The number of free variables can be up to 40.\n\nFor the GF(p) case, the minimum sum problem is: minimize sum(x_i) + sum(pivotFunc_r(x)) over x in GF(p)^numFree. Each pivotFunc_r is a linear function of the free variables modulo p.\n\nThis is equivalent to: minimize a linear function over an a